by the 'historical structural' approach, this study seeks to understand how and why the international community continuously reinterprets or redefines the UN's role with regard to intra-state conflicts. The study concentrates on intra-states 'peacekeeping environments', and examines what changes, if any, have occurred to the normative basis of UN peacekeeping in intra-state conflicts from the early 1960s to the early 1990s. One of the original aspects of the study is its analytical framework, where the conceptualisation of 'normative basis' revolves around objectives, functions and authority, and is closely connected with the institutionalised values in the UN Charter such as state sovereignty, human rights and socio-economic development.This book is essential reading for postgraduate students of IR and international peacekeeping organisations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivil wary20th century. 0aHumanitarian intervention. 0aPeacekeeping forces. 0aPolitical sciencezglobalxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 4aPolitical Studies 2021. 4aSecurity, Conflict & Peace 2018. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Peace.2bisacsh  aUN Charter.  aUN peacekeeping.  aUnited Nations.  agovernance.  ainstitutionalised values.  ainternational community.  aintra-state conflicts.  anormative basis.  apeace.  asecurity.1 aAksu, Eşref, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526137906zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526137906zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cov